RIP John Mayall

Sad to say goodbye to John Mayall. He was a pivotal force in the 1960s British blues movement. His extensive 70 year career brought us around 100 albums and many blues superstars emerged from their time in his band. He has been referred to as the Godfather of British Blues and the founder of Blues-Rock. He passed away yesterday at age 90. John was active up until about a year ago. Rest in peace John Mayall. Thank you for your many contributions. A well-lived life!

Photo tribute to George Harmonica Smith!

Please enjoy this wonderful tribute to a great harmonica player that Bob Corritore is putting together. Right now we have a pretty good start going, but thereâ€™s much more to do. If any of our readers have any great photos or paraphernalia regarding George Harmonica Smith that they would be willing to allow us to use for this page, it would be greatly appreciated. Just click reply with any submissions and thank you! Click here to see the page so far.

This highly influential harmonica player would become a stylistic template for West Coast harmonica players. Born in West Helena, Arkansas, George would land in Chicago and Kansas City before making California is permanent home. In addition to his great recordings as a singer and frontman, he was also a prominent sideman making records with Muddy Waters, Otis Spann, Big Mama Thornton, Big Joe Turner, Little Johnny Taylor, Jesse Thomas, Champion Jack Dupree, Eddie Taylor, Lonesome Sundown, T-Bone Walker and Sunnyland Slim. He was a teacher and father figure to Rod Piazza and William Clarke. Please enjoy these wonderful photos of this great harmonica player!

Blues Blogger from Russia reviews Crawlinâ€™ Kingsnake.

Olegsâ€™s Blues Blog (Russia)

June 14, 2024

English translation:

Eleven years ago, John Primer (79) and Bob Corritore (67) began their collaboration. This spring they released their fourth album together with the brand new â€˜Crawlinâ€™ Kingsnakeâ€™. During these 11 years, both elderly gentlemen won many awards in the field of blues, and now they have recorded an old-school blues disc.

It has eleven covers and one song written by John Primer (â€œHiding Placeâ€). The album begins with the track â€œTake A Messageâ€, which immediately makes us understand what awaits us. Two blues electric guitars, Johnâ€™s warm Mississippi voice, and Bob making the most of his harmonica.

Next is John Lee Hookerâ€™s â€œCrawlinâ€™ Kingsnakeâ€, followed by Willie Dixonâ€™s â€œDown In The Bottomâ€. The album included three covers of Muddy Waters, including the dynamic track â€œStuff You Gonna Watchâ€ and â€œRosalee Bluesâ€, a slow blues starring Anthony Geraci on piano. â€œGravel Roadâ€ and â€œFeel Like Going Homeâ€ complete the traditional blues album.

Both Primer and Corritore are at the peak of their careers: Primer was recently inducted into the Blues Hall of Fame, as well as receiving numerous awards and a Grammy nomination. Likewise, Corritore has been active in European festivals, releasing five critically acclaimed albums in 2023, being the subject of numerous articles, receiving numerous nominations, and even winning in some places.

The band sounds like Muddy Watersâ€™ band in its heyday, and with its playing it proves once again (or tries to prove) that such blues will always exist. At least, with this album they completely convinced me!

RIP Gary Wright, the ultimate friend and blues fan.

Last week we lost Gary Wright after his long battle fighting cancer. Gary was the ultimate goodwill ambassador for the Blues. He moved from California to Phoenix about 12 years ago and immediately became part of the Rhythm Room family. He was a chef and often brought wonderful freshly-cooked meals to greet touring musicians in the green room. His enthusiasm for blues, music and musicians was unstoppable, and his kindness to all people was universal. The Rhythm Room will host a musical memorial to Gary on the afternoon of Saturday, February 24 at 12:30 pm. Playing at this show are Cadillac Assembly Line, Big Daddy D & The Dynamites, Gypsy Wild At Harp, George Bowman, Smokestack Lightning, Brian Fahey, Johnny Rapp, Bluesman Mike, Mike Simpson, Mike Howard, Rocket 88s, Yahni Riley, Jimi Primetime Smith, Bob Corritore, and more! Event poster is forthcoming. Rest in peace dear Gary.
